\todo{didn't I already write about the similarity to Latin stress rules here and the possibility of them being due to contact?} 

Just as in Classical Latin, stress ends up on the penult if it is \textit{heavy}, which is to say if it contains either a long vowel or at least one consonant in its coda, as demonstrated in Table \ref{tab:CPAstressOntoPenult} with various reflexes of earlier Greek loans. 
The phenomenon of course would not be limited to Greek loans, but exact stress placement in etyma inherited from Proto-Indo-European at this time is less secure.
It may also be seen in \modAlbGloss{kashtë}{thatch}, reflecting a PIE *\textit{kolH-es-t\'e\ha}, which may have been indirectly attested in a gloss of Hesychius, `kast\'on' \todo{greek letters!} (\citet[249]{huld1986strata}; \citet[213]{demiraj1997aed}).  
Meanwhile, also as in Latin, when the penult was not strong (`weak'), stress instead moved into the antepenult, as seen in \todo{Greek gloss} \jandaJosephGloss \modAlbGloss{mok\"er}{millstone}. 

