There is also some evidence in reflexes of Greek loans of stress \textit{advancement} onto heavy penults, as seen in *\textit{m\'aradrja} `fennel' (\S\ref{WestGrLoans}) > *\textit{mar\'adrja} \jandaJosephArrow \textit{mërrajë} id., rather than *\textit{marr\"ej\"e} or **\textit{marre}. 
While these could in theory be placed into APA as they don't seem to impact Latin loans, tehre is also no reason to, and they do seem to produce adherence to a system close to the Classical Latin stress system.

That is not to say all of these stress movements did, however.
One evident stress advancement rule that does not quite align to the rules of Classical Latin is the advancement of stress from a stressed vowel followed by a prelateral /o/ onto the o.
However, this is also seen in various Romance languages. \todo{check if this happened in Romanian and French! / remark about it. } 
